  "summary": "Fearing that Bobby has met with foul play, Frankie drives toward Stafali in a state of turmoil after discovering he left only a telegram and no message. Meanwhile, at a hotel, a man and a janitor speculate that a wealthy man has abandoned a woman he was meant to marry in secret.\n\nDuring an inquest into a death ruled a suicide due to mental illness, Frankie and Roger testify. Dr. Nicholson presents a farewell letter as evidence, leading the jury to deliver a sympathetic verdict. Frankie notes a connection between this case and another suicide involving insanity. After the widow, Sylvia, retires, Frankie informs Roger that Bobby is missing. When Dr. Nicholson arrives and praises the coroner, Dr. Davidson, Roger confronts him, asserting that his brother was murdered by someone who lured him into drug addiction. Frankie observes the doctor's reaction and begins to question the validity of his alibis, which rely on Sylvia's testimony. When Frankie mentions that her driver, Hawkins, has gone missing near Granchester, Nicholson dismisses the claim as unreliable gossip.\n\nUpon returning to the hall, Frankie finds a letter in Bobby's handwriting. In it, Bobby claims to have found a clue and instructs her to travel to Tudor Cottage in Chipping Sodbury by train rather than her conspicuous Bentley, emphasizing that she must not tell anyone. While relieved that Bobby is likely safe, Frankie becomes suspicious of Roger; she fears that Bobby's heavy emphasis on secrecy implies Roger might have unwittingly betrayed them.",
